  "prompt": "I'm 4 years into my H1B, my GC is not yet started. If I apply GC through consulting company, do I need to join this company before filing I-140/I485?",
  "response": "In general, when applying for a Green Card (GC) through a consulting company, the process typically involves several steps, including filing the PERM Labor Certification, I-140 (Immigrant Petition for Alien Worker), and I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence or Adjust Status). Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **PERM Labor Certification**: This is the first step in the employment-based Green Card process. The consulting company must file this on your behalf, attesting that there is a lack of qualified U.S. workers for the position and that hiring you will not adversely affect the wages and working conditions of U.S. workers.\n\n2. **I-140 Petition**: After the PERM Labor Certification is approved, the consulting company can file an I-140 petition. This petition establishes that you have a permanent job offer from the company and that you meet the qualifications for the position.\n\n3. **I-485 Adjustment of Status**: Once the I-140 is approved and your priority date is current, you can file the I-485 to adjust your status to that of a Green Card holder.\n\nRegarding your specific question about joining the consulting company before filing the I-140/I-485:\n\n- **Before Filing I-140**: Typically, you do not need to be employed by the consulting company before they file the I-140 petition. However, the company must have a bona fide job offer for you, and they must intend to employ you in the offered position when your Green Card is granted.\n\n- **Before Filing I-485**: You generally do not need to be employed by the consulting company when filing the I-485. However, similar to the I-140 petition, the company must have a genuine intention to employ you once your Green Card is approved.\n\n**Important Considerations**:\n- **Intent**: Both you and the consulting company must intend for you to take up the offered position once you receive your Green Card.\n- **Job Offer Validity**: The job offer must remain valid throughout the Green Card process.\n\nIt is highly recommended that you consult with an immigration attorney to ensure that you understand the requirements and nuances of the process, as well as to ensure compliance with all regulations and to address any specific circumstances related to your case.",
